was from going to these meetups.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
So this is now the tough part of the journey.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Okay, going back to the hiking metaphor, we've discovered that there's wildlife,

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
and it can actually eat humans.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
So, you know, we're going to have to be careful.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
So my first encounter with MLOps, well, what is it, first of all?

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
So it stands for Machine Learning Operations.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:39.000
And the idea is that it streamlines the machine learning lifecycle.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
So the idea is we train our models.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:47.000
We want that model to be usable, so we deploy it to the cloud,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:49.000
where users can query it.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
So we'll have some sort of model API.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And then we also want to monitor the model while it's in production.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So we want to check that as the data changes,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
is the model still maintaining an acceptable accuracy?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
And if it's not, then we need to make sure we're retraining it

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:07.000
at a regular frequency.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Another big part of this, as well, is because this is like a cycle,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
and we're constantly retraining our models,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
it becomes very important to version and to store our models,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.000
because we want to be able to retrieve a model from any point in time in the past.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
If these models are leading to important decision-making in businesses,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:26.000
it's very important to see why a certain decision was made,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and what was it about that model that led to that prediction.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
So that's pretty much all there is to it, really, in words.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:35.000
It sounds simple enough.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.000
Until we see our first architecture diagram.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
So this is like a very typical sort of architecture diagram.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
I actually just used a diagram that my friend put together.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
He'll not mind.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
But essentially, the way these work is they basically summarize

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.000
the full infrastructure of like a machine learning sort of lifecycle or workflow.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
So usually there's some version control stuff,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:03.000
in this case with GitHub, sort of around the top.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Then you're going to have some stuff to do with like development environment.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:11.000
There's going to be a staging environment somewhere, production environment.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
But, yeah, for like a beginner data scientist, when I look at this,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
it might as well just be squiggly lines, you know, just spaghetti.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:20.000
You know, I don't really know what's going on.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
These words, I don't recognize them.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
You know, what's easy to, you know, it's just, you know, I don't know.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.000
It might as well just be like symbols, you know.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
At the meetups, we have lots of free pizza to encourage high attendance.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
And as the organizer, I never get enough pizza at the start of the meetups.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So at this point, I just start to think about pizza flavors, you know,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.000
like what I should have picked, you know, before it all started.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.000
So, yeah.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So there is just an uncomfortable reality for a lot of beginners in data science

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
that, and this was also touched on in Flavia's brilliant talk just before mine,

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
there's an overwhelming choice when it comes to data science.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
So particularly with modeling frameworks, you know, do I go tidy models?

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Do I go R or Python?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
You know, which package am I going to use?

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
What type of model will I use?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Then there's cloud platforms.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
Do I use Azure? Do I use AWS?

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
You know, it's an endless choice.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
And there's so many different options for creating environments and containers,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
and the list just goes on.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
It's also very multidisciplinary.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:28.000
So, you know, this demands expertise in data science on the modeling side,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
but also in like cloud infrastructure.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
So actually setting up, you know, compute environments,

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:39.000
setting like the, you know, the optimal computing power, that sort of thing.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:41.000
So unless you've got a big team around you,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.000
it's very difficult to know how to jump into this area.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:45.000
It's also very expensive.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:47.000
You know, all these cloud platforms charge money.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
You know, none of these are free.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
There might be a few free trials out there,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
but, you know, it's very difficult to jump into this.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So where do you even begin?

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So about that part of the journey, you know, it's been hard going.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
We're going to just persevere, though.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
You know, even though we forgot the bug spray,

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:06.000
we're getting eaten alive by insects, you know.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.000
Can't get a good night's sleep, but we're going to just keep on going.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:13.000
So let's get to grips with MLOps.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
So just to add some extra motivation and incentive,

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:21.000
in 2024, I agreed to deliver an MLOps workshop at an upcoming conference.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
I say I agreed to this.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
Actually, it was the CTO of Jumping Rivers, Colin.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:31.000
He signed up to do a workshop, and then he asked me to do it in his place.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And he was very positive about, you know,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
he saw lots of benefits from doing this.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
You know, it means you'll get to learn it.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.000
You can start to teach MLOps as a service.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
And actually, you know what, he has got a point,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
and I would actually argue that if you are learning a really difficult topic,

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:50.000
you know, sign up to do a talk sometime in the future or a workshop.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
It doesn't have to be at a big conference,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
but just at a local data science meetup.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
Because knowing that you're going to be getting up onto a stage,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
you know, presenting it to a large audience, you know,

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
you're going to have to be able to explain it to an audience,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
and so you're going to have to understand it yourself.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:06.000
So I think it is actually probably the best way to learn a new topic

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:09.000
is to just sign up to do a workshop,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:12.000
if you've got any opportunities to do that.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:15.000
So I had no choice now.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:18.000
The turning point in learning MLOps

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
was discovering the Betafair package.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
So this is a package developed by Posit,

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
and like many of their other packages, like Shiny and Quarto,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
it's multilingual, so it's available in both R and Python.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
It's completely free to install and use.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
So it's a really good sort of beginner-friendly package.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
I think this diagram from the Betafair documentation

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
summarizes it really nicely.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
So this is the kind of lifecycle that we have in machine learning.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
So we're collecting data.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.000
We're doing some data cleaning using the Tidyverse.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
We're training the model using Tidy models.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And then we've then got these steps in this kind of shaded background,

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:56.000
and these are the steps that Betafair takes care of.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
So with a single package,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
you've got functions for versioning your models.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
So that will store the models.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
It will store it with the timestamp,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
so you can retrieve your models at any previous time.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
You can store them locally. You can store them on the cloud.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:15.000
It has deployment, so it will use Docker to create a Docker file.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:19.000
It will create a model API using Plumber,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
and it's got functions for deploying this straight to the cloud,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
whether that's Posit Connect or AWS.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
It's also got functions for monitoring your models.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
So you can basically track metrics like the accuracy

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:34.000
or the root mean square error in real time as the data changes.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
In the background, it's using lots of other packages.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
So it's using pins for the versioning.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:42.000
It's using Plumber if it's R or FastAPI if it's Python

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
to actually set up the model API,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
and it's also generating the Docker file for you.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So even if you're not an expert in Docker

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
and creating container environments,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
it does a lot of this heavy lifting for you,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:58.000
which I think is really nice.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
It also has the option to deploy your models to the local host.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
So if you're not ready to invest in cloud infrastructure,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
just deploy it onto your local machine,

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
and you can still query it as though it's an API

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
just using just the local host IP address.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
It's just a nice way to sort of get used to working with APIs

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
and to check that the model actually behaves as expected,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
and it's completely free to do this.

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
Once you're happy then with your model and it's working as expected,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.000
then you can start to think about that next step.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
So yeah, I think this is a really great beginner-friendly way

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
to learn MLOps.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So going back to that workshop that I was signed up to teach.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
So the way we did this,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
it's quite similar to how we run our training courses at Jumping Rivers.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So we use Pulsate Workbench,

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
where attendees can use Jupyter if it's Python,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
or RStudio if they're using R.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
All the dependencies are pre-installed,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
so no one has to install anything.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:52.000
So both R and Python attendees are welcome.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
We only really did deployments to the local host

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.000
just to sort of teach them what an API is,

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
how do we query an API, what's a POST request,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
what's a GET request, that kind of thing.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And the feedback I've had is that the attendees have found it really clear

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
to understand and sort of pitch to the right level.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.000
So I'm really pleased with how that's gone.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
So we're approaching the end of the journey.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
Back to civilization.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
Never been so happy to see a Walmart,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
as you can see from my face in this picture.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
But we're not going to stop here.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:26.000
So we've taken this forward.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
We've not just left at that one workshop.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So I've now taught three workshops at conferences over the past year,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
and also I'm now giving this talk today.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
We're also now wrapping up our first MLOps project for a client.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
I'm not going to show you an architecture diagram for this,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
but basically it's Python models deployed in AWS, essentially.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And it's gone very well, so we're very happy with that.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
We're also now starting to build up an MLOps server,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Jumping Rivers, where explainability will be a key idea of it.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
So just making sure that the client is fully informed of the process

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.000
and explaining the concepts to them in an understandable sort of manner.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
So we've already got data science and cloud engineering at Jumping Rivers,

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
so this is essentially bridging these two areas.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So, yeah, we're very excited to be developing this,

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
and we're excited to share more information about this in the very near future.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So just to give a quick summary,

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.000
you can get started in MLOps right now with free and open-source tools,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
so check out Vetiver if you're interested

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:27.000
in a really beginner-friendly package to get started.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.000
Architecture diagrams can be incredibly useful for the right use cases,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:36.000
but do consider the audience at the conference or the meetup that you're going to,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and just consider whether you do need to have all of the information in that diagram.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
Of course, there's nothing wrong with just fashioning it up quickly

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:45.000
and just in case anyone wants to take a photograph,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:51.000
it's quite a lot of information to be talking through in just one slide.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And finally, signing up to teach a workshop or to give a talk,

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
it's a really good way to learn a topic,

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:01.000
so I can highly recommend having a go at teaching if you've never tried that.

