00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
Okay, a quick question or two.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Do you know of anyone who has had to rescind a model

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
and fall back to the previous version?

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.000
No, I've not come across any cases like that.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
Like I said, it's still quite a new service in Jumping Rivers,

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
so I think the longer we spend in this area,

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
we will start to see some more cases like this,

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
but yeah, it's a core part of MLOps

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
that you always want models to be retrievable at any point.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
Unexpected things can happen.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:13.000
You might suddenly change your mind

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
and want to go back to where you were, so yeah.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
Okay, one more.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
I'm an early career data scientist

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.000
who wants experience with MLOps,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:26.000
but my organization doesn't focus on deploying models.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:31.000
We do more one-off research.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
What advice do you have to practice MLOps

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
without organizational support?

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:38.000
Yeah, so like I said,

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:39.000
the Vetiver package is a really good way

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
just to start learning the concepts at least.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
It's completely free to install.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.000
It's a bit limited in that

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
if you actually want to start practicing on the cloud,

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
Vetiver is not going to just automatically

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
let you deploy things straight to AWS and connect,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:57.000
so I think just to get used to the concepts,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
it's a really good way to get started at least.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
I'm still looking for that answer as to like

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
how does a complete beginner take that next step

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:06.000
going onto the cloud,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
so if anyone does have any suggestions or ideas about that,

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
I'd be really interested to hear them afterwards.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
It's like somebody should do a workshop.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:15.000
